    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In traditional literature, the term ceyang is primarily used in the Yingzao fashi (1103) of the Song dynasty. Literally meaning “side appearance” (Kroll 2005 35, 534), it refers to the view of architectural frameworks or components from the side perpendicular to the roof ridge, which is then expressed in the form of a drawing (Li 2009, 5.19b, 30.6a-7a, 31.3a-6a).</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
